{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170975/1938012001/0041.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nURGES KILLING,\nNOT MODIFYING\nPROFITS LEVY\nN. Y. Board of Trade\nSpokesman Also Would\nBroaden Income Tax Base,\nHe Tells House Committee\nWashington, Jan. 17\u2014(AP) \u2014The\nfirst business spokesman at public\nhearings on the administration-ap\nproved tax revision plan advised\nCongress today to kill the undis\ntributed profits tax instead of modi\nfying it and to broaden the base of\nincome taxes.\n-let It Die\u201d\nM. L. Seldman, chairman of the tax\ncommittee of the New York Board\nof Trade, was the first private wit\nness. before the House ways and\nmeans committee.\n\u201cThe undistributed profits tax\nstands before the country today\nthoroughly convicted as an undesir\nable tax and as harmful to business\nand to confidence,\" he said. \u201cIt has\nearned its execution, let it die.\"\nThe recommendations on which the\nconrmil tee is conducting hearings\nwould lift the levy from corporations\nhaving incomes of less than {26,000 a\nyear, hut retain its principle for big\ncorporations.\nSeidman also called for abolition of\nthe present system under which cap\nitai gains are lumped with a tax\npayer's other income and subjected\nto income taxes.\nAs a means of making the people\nconscious of taxes and of the fact\nthat it is their money the federal\ngovernment spends, the New Yorker\nproposed a broadening of the income\ntax base. The people then would pay\ndirectly what they now pay in indi\nrect taxation, he said.\nHe suggested specifically that per\nsonal exemptions and allowances for\ndependents be cut in half and that\na 10 per cent surtax on incomes of\nmore than S4OOO be raised.\n\u201cThis is an election year,\u201d Repre\nsentative Crowther (R., N. Y.) re\nminded him. \"You know that they're\nnot going to broaden the tax base in\nan election year.\u201d\n\u201cYon\u2019re Just Wasting Yonr Time\u201d\nNoting that the suggestion would\nbring married men making more than\n$1250 and single men making more\nthan SBOO a year within the income\ntax range, Representative Dingell\n<D\u201e Mich.) told the witness:\n\"So far as I\u2019m concerned, you\u2019re\nJust wasting your time.\u201d\nChairman Vinson (D., Ky.) r of the\ntax subcommittee, read from hearings\nin 1936 on the undistributed profits\nlevy in which Seidman said the New\nYork Board of Trade considered the\ntax \"sound tn principle.\u201d\nHowever, Seidman said he had op\nposed putting it into effect at that\ntime.\nWould Favor Flat Tax\nWhen committeemen questioned\nwhether the alternative of an increase\nof one-half of 1 per cent in the nor\nmal corporate income tax rates would\nproduce sufficient revenue, the wit\nness said he would favor a flat cor\nporate income tax of 22 Vi per cent\nover any form of undistributed prof\nits tax. He also said he would favor\nthe subcommittee's recommendations\nover present law.\nBenjamin C. Marsh, executive sec\nretary of the People\u2019s lobby of Wash\nington. testified there would be a\n\u201cpanic\u201d unless the \u201cdespicably brutal\ntax policies of the present administra\ntion\" were altered promptly. But he\nfavored retention of the undistributed\nprofits tax, with some exemptions for\nsmall, efficient concerns which used\nsurpluses to retire debt. He asked\nparticularly for repeal or drastic re\nduction of \u201cail federal consumption\ntaxes\u201d and Imposition, in their place,\nof an excise tax on land values and\nincreased income and estate lax os.\nPersonal Service Companies\nA Barr Comstock, speaking for a\npersonal service company of Cam\nbridge, Mass., asked exemption from\npersonal holding company surtaxes of\nincome received by personal service\nstock in an enterprise given them as\nfirms in selling at a gain development\ncompensation. Without that exemp\ntion. he said, the nt'.nlbuted pr\ntax of 85 and 75 per cent on per\nsonal holding companies would mean\n\u25a0practically a death sentence\" to per\nsonal service firms.\nSeidman. amplifying his point about\nlowering income tax exemptions, told\nthe committee that if these exemp\ntions and credits for dependents had\nbeen in effect in 1934, the number of\ntaxable returns for Incomes under\n$5,000 would have been 8.000.000 in\nstead of 1,000,000.\nFEEL HOLDING COMPANY\nELIMINATION IMPOSSIBLE\nObservers See Little Hope\nof Carrying Out Program\nof Roosevelt\nWashington, Jan. 16\u2014(AP) \u2014Some\nadministration advisers in Congress\nexpressed belief today that it would\nbe impossible to carry out President\nRoosevelt\u2019s idea that all holding com\npaniees should be abolished.\nOne usually well-informed admin\nistration supporter said privately that\nhe doubted any holding company leg\nislation would be sought by the\nPresident at the present session. He\npointed out that an extensive Roose\nvelt program already was pending tn\nCongress and that a new holding\ncompany bill might develop long\ndrawn out controversy.\nSome other supporters of the\nPresident said they thought Rny leg\nislation to abolish holding companies\nshould apply only to those in the\nbanking and insurance fields.\nMay Test Present Act\nIn the utilities Held, they said, it\nprobably would be desirable to test\nthe operation of the present holding\ncompany act for a year or so before\nnew legislation was considered.\nThe existing law limits to two the\nnumber of holding companies which\ncan be superimposed on a group of\nutility operating companies.\nRailroad holding companies now\nare being scrutinized by a special\nSenate investigating committee of\nwhich Senator Wheeler (D., Mont.)\nis chairman. Several legislators ex\npressed a disposition to await, the\ncommittee's recommendations before\nseeking holding company legislation\naffecting railroads.\nThese persons said It probably\nwould be undesirnhls to prohibit\n\u2018first degree\u2019\u2019 rail holding companies,\nbecause without these It would he\ndifficult, to carry out the govern\nment's railroad coordination policies.\nU.S. CHAMBER HITS\nBLAMING BUSINESS\nFOR THE RECESSION\nSays Latter \u2018Has Shown Re\nstraint\u2019 by Not Replying in\nSame Tenor \u2014More White\nHouse Visits Set\nWashington. Jan. 15\u2014(AP)\u2014 The\nChamber of Commerce of the United\nStates reprimanded the administra\ntion today for \"the recent tendency\nto assail business and blame it for the\nrecession.\"\nThis tendency \"has not proved con\nducive to the cooperative spirit so es\nsential to confidence and recovery,\"\nthe chamber said in its periodical\nWashington review.\n\"Scolding and name-calling do not\nmake for team-play between busi\nness and government. They don\u2019t put\nmen to work.\u201d\n\"Business, on its part, has shown\na discreet restraint in not aggravat\ning the situation by replying to the\nattacks in the same tenor,\u201d the or\nganization of businessmen added.\nThe administration is \u201cgt\u00abping\u201d for\na way out of the business decline and\nis examining suggestions for a new\ntype of planning legislation. pat\nterned \u201csomewhat after the NRA con\ncept,\" the chamber said.\nMore White House Visits\nBusinessmen wiil trek in increas\ning numbers to the White House next\nweek to discuss recovery methods.\nLast week, they arrived in groups\nof two to five but on AVednesday 50\nbusiness leaders who belong to the\nPresident\u2019s business advisory council\nare scheduled to go to the executive\nmansion as a group.\nThis conference is expected gen\nerally to cover such topics as in\ndustrial planning, Instalment selling,\nmonopoly, utilities, housing and la\nbor policies. No intimation has leaked\nout, as to what specific proposals may\nbe discussed.\nBut the President has indicated\nhe is seeking a method of industrial\nplanning which would enable business\nmen to gear their activities closer to\nthe nation's needs and thus minimize\nthe economic cycle of boom and de\npression. Part of the proposal may\nbe to limit high-pressure salesman\nship and restrict instalment financ\ning.\nOne of the methods under considera\ntion would permit businessmen to\ncooperate in studying markets and\nproduction needs without fear of\nprosecution under the antitrust laws\nunless they fixed prices or elimin\nated competition. Before adopting\nsuch a system, the businessmen\nwould present it to a governmental\nagency for a ruling that it did not\nviolate the monopoly statutes.\nNew Tax Forms Scorned\nBy Debt-Free Nebraska\nAdvocates of \u2018New-Fangled Ideas\u2019 Frequently Arise\nBut Government Continues to Operate On Pay-as-\nYou-Go Plan\nBy PAUL YVELLYIAX\nLincoln, Neb.. Jan. 11 \u2014There is an\nold saying that \u201cYVhat you don\u2019t know\ndoesn\u2019t hurt you.\" which seems to be\nthe philosophy behind the mu4titude\nof indirect, hidden and freak taxes\nwhich within the last few years have\nswept the country. The feeling is that,\nso long as the taxpayer does not real\nize what is happening to him, he can\nhe mulcted with far greater abandon\nthan if he knows how much he is\npaying.\nConcerning this matter, Nebraska\nhas an attitude which is skeptical, not\nto say distrustful. As Gov R. L.\nCochran sums up the feeling of Ne\nbraskans on the subject of taxes:\n\"We often hear it said that taxes\nare painful. I am not sure hut that\ntaxes should be painful in order to\nmake the people tax conscious. The\ngeneral sales tax lays its heaviest bur\nden on the men and women who toil,\nand because this tax is paid painless\nly with each purchase, the revenue is\noften spent less carefully than the\nrevenue from more painful taxes,\nwhere the citizen is jvatchful and\nconscious of the total annual cost.\nExperience has shown that levying\na general sales tax and a state in\ncome tax on top of a property tax\nis conducive to more liberal spending\nand therefore increased costs of gov\nernment.\"\nNew-Fangled Ideas Offered\nIt would, of course, be wrong to as\nsume that all Nebraskans think as\nGov Cochran thinks. It follows,\ntherefore, that frequently there arise\nadvocates of the new-fangled ideas\nin taxation. Thus far. however, the\ngreat majority of Nebraskans has\ntaken an extremely jaundiced view\ntoward such proposals.\nIn 1934, Gov Cochran, then state\nengineer, made his first gubernatorial\nrace on a platform of opposition to\nnew forms of taxation. The citizens\nelected him, and then reelected him in\n1936. They have hacked him consis\ntently in his fiscal policies.\nThe Nebraska analysis of the tax\nproblem Is fundamental:\nGovernment is necessary for the\nmaintenance of organized society. Tax\nation is necessary for the maintenance\nof government. But in government\nthere should lie a practical applica\ntion of economy as well as efficiency,\nand while it is the duty and the pride\nof the citizen to pay for every essen\ntial of government, It Is criminal to\nlevy taxes simply to waste the funds\nraised by them.\nThere are three main sources of rev.\nenue to the state: Property taxes\ngasoline taxes, and beer and liquor\ntaxes. There are also some small rev\nenues. such as fees and tuitions re\nceived by the university and normal\nschools, and various corporation li\ncense and inspection tees.\nScrutinizes New Activities\nNebraska operates a modern and\nefficient government. But the state\ncarefully scrutinizes every new ac\ntivity. and the proposed appropriations\nfir it, before It embarks upon it. As\nGovernor Cochran explains the stale's\nposition:\n\"Pressure to Increase governmental\nactivities and thereby to Increase\ngovernmental expenses comes from\ntwo directions, from expending agen\ncies within the government Itself and\nfrom minority pressure groups out\nside. It Is easy and natural for any\nexpending agency of government,\nwhether for education, social security,\ncharitable nnd penal Institutions, puh\nllc assistance of any kind, highway\nconstruction or any one of the other\nexpending agencies, to become en\nthusiastic over a particular activity\nThe demand may he for a new ac\ntivity: the demand may be for ln\nexsased expenditures under an old\nactivity. However, none of these ex-\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, JANUARY 20, 1938\nLAMONTS TALK HELD A REPLY\nOF BIG BUSINESS TO NEW DEAL\nIntelligent People Said to Realize Capital\u2019s Greatest\nFailure Is Fact It Has Not Coordinated Its Sys\ntem to Prevent Unemployment\nNew York, Jan. 18\u2014In his talk yes\nterday at. the University of Pennsyl\nvania luncheon, Thomas W. Lamont,\nfor the first time since President\nRoosevelt took office, expressed pub\nlicly what might be called a reply by\nbig bnsiiw ss :o tlv\nfrom the viewpoint of a partner of\nJ. P. Morgan Co. What Lamont\nsaid yesterday has additional interest\nbecause he was a member of the\ngroup that included Owen D. Young\nand John L. Lewis, who conferred\nwith President Roosevelt late Friday\nto seek cooperation between the gov\nernment, business and labor to end\nthe recession.\nIn his column today, Walter Lipp\nmann, in discussing the White House\nconference of Friday, said of Lamont:\n\u201cMr Lamont, if we are to believe im\naginative artists belonging to the\nschool of Secretary Ickes, is the head\nand front of a gigantic capitalistic\nnetwork which reaches out to control\npractically every activity of the Amer\nican people.\" Exaggeration by new\ndealers in talking about \"industrial\nroyalists\" is to be expected. Wall\nstreet knows, however, that if there\nis any such thing as an industrial roy\nalist. Lamont is one of them. Hence\nWall street\u2019s interest in what Lamont\nsaid yesterday.\nOne point that the active partner of\nthe Morgan firm made was that capi\ntal is not on a strike, as recently has\nbeen charged by high administration\nofficials. He said capital had been\n\u201clocked out\u201d by various new deal\nmeasures; that to say capital is on a\nstrike is about as wide of the mark\nas to say that \"30,000 employes, who\nhad lost their Jobs because of slack\norders had gone on a strike.\u201d\nThen Lamont got down to his real\nsubject. Intelligent, people In and out\nof the financial district have no real\nquarrel with the great fortunes of to\nday. They know that there is nothing\nin the \"soapbox\" talk that there should\nbe a division of such fortunes; they\nknow that a division would mean a\ndinner, perhaps a package of cigarets\nfor each citizen; they know that the\nreal indictment against leaders of\ncapital is their failure to iron out the\nhills and valleys of economic and in\ndustrial life to prevent unemployment\nat more or less regular periods, there\nby resulting in loss of economic inde\npendence for millions of people.\nIn his talk yesterday Lamont ad\nmits this: \"Undoubtedly at. times they\nhave been lacking in foresight, as for\nexample, in matters of labor policy.\"\nthe Morgan partner said, adding: \u201cA\ngreat responsibility rests upon us\nbusinessmen to think greatly of our\nfunctions, to carry nut our ideas in\nthe grand manner, with foresight and\nrestraint; to see not only that we are\nnot only the prudent guardians of the\ncapital entrusted to us for safe keep\npending agencies is apt to see the\ntotal cost of government, hence the\nnecessity to view ail of these activi\nties in the light of the total cost,\n\u201cIn this day of multitudinous or\nganizations. when new organizations\nare formed overnight for the purpose\nof bringing pressure to add new bur\ndens to government, it becomes the\ndutv of the executive authority, of the\nlegislative authority, and the local\ngoverning bodies to scrutinize all such\ndemands. It, is their duty to think\nnot only of the benefits to the minor\nity, but of the costs to the majority,\nthe taxpayer and his ability to pay\nthe total cost.\u201d\nPay-As-You-Go Flan\nIn an extraordinarily successful\nmanner, this principle has been car\nried out Nebraska's fiscal policy is\nbased on the pay-as-you-go plan,\nwhereby no state debt is allowed; con\nstitutional and statutory limitations\non local spending; and, finally, a\nsimple, and understandable tax struc\nture. which includes an unyielding op\nposition to soealled new- forms of\ntaxes, such as state income, sales and\ncigaret taxes.\nThe property tax. embracing real,\npersonal and intangible property, is\nthe principal source of revenue to\nthe state and its subdivisions. The\nliquor tax is heavy\u2014the people of\nNebraska feeling that those who wish\nto indulge in this manner should con\ntribute to the general welfare in the\nform of taxes which can be placed\nto some good use. The gasoline tax is\nfive cents a gallon at present, one-half\ncent going to the social security pro\ngram and the remainder to the stale's\npresent heavy road building program,\nbut the motor license fees are com\nparatively small, ranging from $3 to\n$5 a car, and averaging about $4 over\nthe state.\nNebraska has watched many other\nstates adopt new forms of taxation,\nupon the theory and often with the\nstated purpose of replacing existing\ntaxes, it has been the belief of Ne\nbraska that this theory is usually a\nfailure, and that eventually the old\ntaxes will he resumed, leaving the new\ntaxes as simply additional forms of\ntaxation.\n\"We feel that the Income tax should\nhe reserved to the federal govern\nment,\" says Governor Cochran. \u201cWe\nfeel that this is particularly true be\ncause of the possibility, if not the\nprobability, that the federal govern\nment will find it necessary to look to\nthis source for increased revenue In\nthe future.\"\nNot Free Front Troubles\nNebraska, however. Is not tree from\ntax troubles. The st\u00dfte has for sev\neral years boon In the grip of a\ndrouth. Like all other states. Nebras\nka has received benefits from the\nfederal government during the de\npression years, and. because of the\nserious curtailment In agricultural\nproduction in a state which Is primar\nily agricultural this federal assiat\nance is welcome.\nin spite of the assistance, however,\ncoupled with the fact that the 1936\ngeneral property levy for the state\nwas only 1.76 mills, collections have\nbeen slow. On October 1. 1937, tilt\nstate tax commissioner's record\nshowed that the collections were 4% j\nper cent below the same date In the\nprevious yeaThe 1937 levy was In\ncreased to J. 64 mills, due to the social\nsecurity program, to which the entire\nreceipts from the beer and liquor\ntaxes have boon assigned by the leg\nislature. This is still a low levy com\npared with many states; nnd the Ne\nbraska administrative officers have no\ngreat amount of worry over the sit\nuation. Nebraska now, as in the pnst,\nhas n way of always paying Its obit\ngat ions.\n[Copyright, 1938, by NANA, luc.j\ning and return, but that our enter\nprises are so ordered in their organ\nization and practices as to fit in with\nthe changing social requirements of\nour age.\"\nLamont did not quarrel with the ef\nforts of government to bring order\nwhere leaders of capital had failed.\nWhat he did say, however, was that\nhe believed the average businessman\nand citizen feels \"that programs of\nreform can certainly be carried into\neffect without the adoption of meth\nods so swift and\ndisturb the actual economy and the\nnormal processes of the country's\ngrowth\": that moreover, there is a\nshrinking away \u201cfrom bureaucracy\u201d\nwhich attempts to \"actually manage\nour daily affairs for us; to tell us\nthat there is in government a wisdom\nso omniscient that it can foresee and\nhandle the varying conditions of\ncommerce and industry throughout the\nvast areas jjt our country stretching\nfrom the Atlantic to the Pacific.\u201d\nR. L. BARNUM.\nWEEKLY REVIEW\nOF BOND MARKET\nBroad Improvement in\nPrices Noted Despite a\nContinued Slump in Some\nRail Loans\nNew York, Jan. 18\u2014(AP) \u2014Broad\nimprovement in bond prices continued\nlast week in spite of a further slump\nin a number of rail loans.\nBuying activities centered chiefly\non low yield corporate liens, United\nStates governments and a sizable\ngroup of second utilities and indus\ntrials. Motivating the good demand,\ntrading circles said, were scattered\nsigns of Improvement in industry, and\nbrighter prospects for revival in the\nmarket for new' offerings.\nMarking the first important new\nbond offering of 1938 underwriters\nwere reported to have met a good\nreception with a $30,000,000 Consoli\ndated Edison issue of 3Vis.\nRails were discouraged from par\nticipation in the upswing by a further\nflow of selling in loans of Baltimore\nOhio. Erie and other important car\nriers. In some instances losses were\nsevere, although the market was more\norderly than in the previous week.\nSome Erie issues broke sharply as an\naftermath of the January 1 interest\ndefault.\nA consistent rise in United States\ngovernments attracted attention, and\nit was noted in investment circles the\nfederal list had moved forward with\nlittle interruption for about a month\nin face of uncertain movements in\nother sections of the investment list\nMILK MARKET HEAD\nx GIVES PRICE REPORT\nFarmers Serving Hub Area\nReceived $2,135 for 3.7\nPer Cent Grade Last Month\nBoston, Jan 12\u2014(AP) \u2014Farmers\nserving the Boston market received\n$2,135 per hundredweight for 3.7 per\ncent milk in the 200-mile zone dur\ning the last half of December. Samuel\nW. Tator, milk market administrator,\nannounced tonight. The average price\nfor December, the administrator said,\nwas $2,303.\nTator reported that in December,\n1936, when the milk marketing agree\nment was not in effect, the prices\npaid by dealers in the 200-mi!e zone\nranged from $2.06 down to $1.62.\nHe announced that the class 2\nprice for the last half of Decem\nber was $1,707. a decrease of about\n14 cents from the previous pay period.\nTltis difference, plus the customary\nfalling off in sales during the holi\nday season, made the difference in\nthe blended price in the first and\nlast halt of the month, the admin\nistrator asserted.\nThe percentage of class 2 milk for\nthe last half of December was 51.8\nper cent, Tator said, while the butter\nfat differential for each point of\ntest above or below- 3.7 per cent was\n4.5 cents per hundredw-eight.\nCOVETED SYMBOL \u2018A\u2019\nSHIFTED TO ANACONDA\nAtchison, Formerly Carry\ning This Designation, Is\nGiven Symbol \u201cSF\u2019\nNew- York, Jan. 13 (AP) \u2014The\ncoveted symbol \"A\" on the stock ex\nchange ticker tape was shifted today\nto capital stock of the Anaconda Cop\nper Mining company, from the com\nmon shares of the Atchison, Topeka\nSanta Fe railway.\nThe Santa Fe stock was designat\ned \"SF,\u201d thus making it more readi\nly recognizable by those who call the\nroad the \u201cSanta Fe\" in.-.tead of the\n\"Atchison.\"\nCommon stock of the Chrysler cor\nporation drew the symbol \u201cC\" here\ntofore assigned to Anaconda Copper.\nChrysler has been \u2019\u2019K\u201d on the tape.\nThe changes were announced by the\ncommittee on arrangements, effective\nthe 24th. Some tape-watchers saw\nthe shift as indication of the In\ncreased trading Interest in copper\nshares the past few years, although\nthe exchange constantly has been re\narranging symbols to make them more\nrepresentative of the companies be\nhind the stocks.\nDUST STORM DAMAGES\nOKLAHOMA\u2019S WHEAT\nOklahoma City, Okl. t .Tan. 14\u2014\nWidespread damag'd to Oklahoma'*\ngrowing: wheat crop was reported to\nday in the wake of the year's first\ndust storm.\nA whirling gale lifted clouds of\nloose silt from the \u201cdust bowl\" area\nand deposited the blowing top soil\nover a wide area of the Oklahoma\nPanhandle and western Kansas.\nWheat was damaged in both Okla\nhoma and Kansas, and the dust was\ndeposited over a half dozen states.\nRed and ftlaek clouds reduced vis\nibility tn a few hundred yards in\nsome regions and blotted out the sun\nat Knid, Okl., and iOakin, Kan.\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stock exchange .779,060\nNew Y ork urb exchange 143,000\nBoston Stock exchange 14,58 S\nSTOCK AVERAGES\n(Compiled by the Associated Press)\nSO 15 15 60\nInd. Kails Util. Stks,\nNet change \u2014A \u2014.5 \u2014i \u2014.4\nTuesday 6K.8 20-5 33.\u00ab 46.6\nPrevious day 67.0 21.0 33. S 47.0\nMonth ago 65. x 21.9 34.1 4\u00abX\nYear ago 97-5 49.1 53.2 71.9\n1937-3 S high 101.6 49.5 54.0 TS.S\n1937.38 low 57.7 48.7 81.6 41.7\n1936 high 99.3 43-5 53.7 72.8\n1936 low 73.4 30.2 43.4 55.7\nMovement In Keeent Years\n1932 low 17.5 8.7 23.9 16.9\n1929 high 146.9 153.9 184.3 157.7\n1927 low 51.6 95.8 61.8 61.8\nNew York, Jan, 16\u2014(AP)\u2014Recov\nery forces again faltered In today\u2019s\nstock market and leading issues\nslipped fraction? to a point or so.\nA sharp break in secondary rail\nroad bonds, following action of the\nErie in filing for reorganization un\nder the federal bankruptcy laws, was\na depressing influence, although most\ncarrier slocks were no worse than\nothers. Erie bonds dropped 2 to 13\npoints. The road\u2019s shares were oft\nabout a point each, the common at\n3%, first preferred 5% and second\npreferred 4.\nA slump in December net operating\nincome for Southern Pacific, one of\n(he first major lines to report for this\nmonth, also was a chilling speculative\ninfluence. While this company's com\nmon shares were down only at\n20H, its bonds were substantially\nlower.\nDespite the scarcity of good news\nfor stocks generally, the volume of\nofferings was exceptionally small,\ni Transfers totaled 779,060 shares\nagainst 933,680 yesterday. It was the\nslimmest turnover for a full day since\nDecember 1. The Associated Press av\nerage of 60 issues was off .4 of a\npoint at 46.6.\nAircrafts and gold mines were re\nsistant throughout, the former still\nreflecting prospects of an expansive\nrearmament program. Homestake\ntouched another new high for more\nthan a year. It finished at 61. Ahead\nalso were Alaska Juneau at 12(6, Mc-\nIntyre 41%, Douglas Aircraft 44%,\nand Glenn Martin 20%.\nWall street appeared hopeful but\nnone too confident that a cooperative\ni plan for business revival w r ould be\nadopted at tomorrow\u2019s conference be\ntween the President and national in\ndustrial chieftains.\nSelling in utilities dried up notably\nnotwithstanding signs of a letup in\nthe administration's antiholding-com\npany campaign were absent.\nSteels and motors were only mildly\nin arrears. Opinions were heard of a\npickup in mill operations in succeed\ning weeks. General Motors put in\nbuying orders for steel to complete\nits first quarter new car output. Be\nlief the business setback would be\nbrief, it was said, inspired Detroit Edi\nson to budget $18,000,000 for new con\nstruction this year, the largest outlay\nsince 1930.\nThe continued French financial cri\nsis was thought to have been some\nwhat of a handicap and the franc fell\nsubstantially in terms of the dollar.\nCommodities on the whole pointed\nlower.\nConspicuous share losers were Beth\nlehcm Steel at 62%. Kennecott 40,\nSanta Fe 38%, Westinghouse 104%\nI and Johns-Manville 79.\n1 Cancelation of price maintenance\nI contracts with dealers by National\nDistillers, presaging a retail price-cut\nting war. knocked over some liquor\nshares. Off a point or more were Na\ntional Distillers at 20%, Schenley 23%,\nand Distillers corporation. 13%.\nBar silver unchanged at 44% cents\n1 an ounce.\nFollowing is a complete list of final\nstock transactions:\nSales in KK>\u2019\u00bb High Low Clow Ch ga\n7 Adams Exp 10% 9% O\u2019i H\n1 Addressor* 21 21 -1\n8 Air Reduction... 57.% 5615 5.%+ 1\n1 Air Way El Ap .1% IVi 1%\n160 Alaska Juneau 12% 12 t2V\u00bb+ S\n2 Alleg'tany Corp .Hi 1% U 4\n6 Allegll pf *3O w-w 14% 14 Wi\u2014\n2 Alleghany pr pf 154. 15% 15% 2\n11 Allegheny Stl 21 26% 2rt%\u2014 1%\n3 Allen Industries 9% 0% 9%\n3 Al Cham Dye 172% 172% liS%-\n8 Allied Mills 14% !4 14%+\n4 Allied Sirs 8% 8% 8%\n1 Do pf 51% 51 51%+ k\n29 Atlla C Mfg 49% 48% 48%-l%\nt Alpha P Cem ..14 14 14\n